When creating a static content macro that serves SVG as in the example below, the image does not end up in the rendered page, because the HTML cleaner seems to remove the SVG tags.

Custom user macros as configured in the Confluence UI can output such SVGs without any issues in contrast.

{code}
    @GET
    @Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_XHTML_XML)
    public Response getSvgData() throws IOException {
        String data = "<svg width=\"100\" height=\"100\">\n"
                + "  <circle cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"40\" stroke=\"green\" stroke-width=\"4\" fill=\"yellow\" />\n"
                + "</svg>";
        return Response.ok("<p>" + data + "</p>").header("Cache-Control", "no-cache").build();
    }
{code}

See the HTML cleaning in this line of the MacroContentManager:
https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/atlassian-connect/src/e86700b1e72a03c2eeb210597a7761129fe4dbf4/confluence/confluence-support/src/main/java/com/atlassian/plugin/connect/confluence/macro/MacroContentManager.java?at=atlassian-connect-parent-1.1.80-connectweek-5&fileviewer=file-view-default#MacroContentManager.java-102

Allowing SVG output would allow us to better integrate with other diagram-related addons in order to produce high-quality vector based images in exported documents.
Since SVG data is static there shouldn't be any security issue with whitelisting SVG tags.

